Every React component re-renders when its parent re-renders ‚Äî that's default behavior. Common causes and fixes:

**1. Unstable references (most common)**
```jsx
// ‚ùå New object/array/function every render
<Child style={{ color: 'red' }} onClick={() => doThing()} />

// ‚úÖ Stable references
const style = useMemo(() => ({ color: 'red' }), []);
const handleClick = useCallback(() => doThing(), []);
<Child style={style} onClick={handleClick} />
```

**2. Missing memoization on the child**
```jsx
// Wrap child so it skips re-render when props haven't changed
const Child = React.memo(function Child({ name }) {
  return <div>{name}</div>;
});
```

`React.memo` does a shallow prop comparison ‚Äî which is why #1 matters. New object references defeat it.

**3. Context changes**
If the child consumes a context whose value is a new object each render, every consumer re-renders. Split contexts or memoize the value:
```jsx
const value = useMemo(() => ({ user, logout }), [user, logout]);
<AuthContext.Provider value={value}>‚Ä¶</AuthContext.Provider>
```

**4. State lifted too high**
If state only affects a subtree, move it down into that subtree so the broader parent doesn't re-render siblings.

**Quick diagnosis:** Add `console.log('render', props)` in the child, or use React DevTools Profiler ‚Üí "Why did this render?" to see exactly which props changed.

